All of you will manage, invest in, work for, or at least purchase goods from, corporations. What is the legal structure and theory of the modern corporation? How is the corporation governed and controlled? How can these mechanisms be improved given the important role that corporations play in our society?

We examine these questions, beginning with an introduction to the basic law of corporations.

We look at the roles of various parties, including shareholders, directors, officers and employees. Our primary focus will be on the duties of corporate directors, and the remedies available when directors do not fulfill their duties.

We then examine some ways in which corporate behavior can be influenced, including the potential influence on corporate activities of public capital markets and a market for corporate control (i.e. mergers and acquisitions), and we consider various methods of monitoring corporate managers such as outside directors and audit committees, whistleblower protections, disclosure requirements to better inform shareholders and other outsiders, and other attempts to improve corporate governance.

Students will be asked to identify and present to the class a presentation on a recent failure of corporate governance -- major frauds, scandals and strategic failures that result in massive loss of value or have major consequences for consumers or other stakeholders -- and to consider the lessons of such failures.

The class will be taught primarily from the perspective of the U.S. legal system (and Delaware corporate law), but with comparative examples from Japan and elsewhere.

現代の会社に関して、その合法的組織構造及び理論とは何か。会社はいかに管理運営されるのか。そのメカニズムはいかに向上されうるか。当講義においては、基本的会社法から始め、これらの点を検討していく。

